Mini chapter summaries
Good Health and Well-Being:
The third sustainable development goal is to ensure healthy lives and promote well being for individuals of all ages.
This goal helps aim to: reduce global maternal mortality rate, end preventable death to newborns, end and help fight against epidemics such as AIDS, tuberculosis, malaria and other communicable diseases, reduce non-communicable diseases, help with prevention of substance abuse, half the number of deaths and injuries from road accidents, ensure universal access to sexual and reproductive health-care services, achieve universal healthcare, and lastly, help reduce the number of deaths from harmful chemicals and pollution. 
These goals are easily achievable by countries with money and access to lots of healthcare services; however, many developing countries struggle to meet these goals because of wealth differences and certain inequalities encountered.
Various determinants of health, including environmental and commercial factors, need attention to pave the way for achieving our common objective of Health for All. 
There are many tradeoffs too when trying to promote better health for all and it's important that the cost of these services don’t outweigh the benefits.
A good example of how important access to good healthcare can be was with the Covid-19 pandemic.
During this period, vaccination rates of newborns and children declined along with an increase in other diseases such as malaria which greatly hurt efforts of SDG 3. 
Along with this, universal healthcare is not present in many countries and access to healthcare in rich countries is sometimes difficult.
Many countries are even experiencing a rise in healthcare costs which makes access to universal healthcare more difficult. 
An increased investment in health systems is needed to support countries in their recovery and build resilience against future health threats.
Also the more healthy individuals within a country are, the more likely their economies are doing well. 
Overall, investment in healthcare by countries' governments can better support health and well-being goals leading to a better society.
